  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented test suite; deviations logged and resolved prior to simulation execution.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 was used under an ISO 13485-aligned quality management system. All solver executables were hash-verified against vendor release checksums. A documented test suite of 14 canonical cases was executed and passed prior to the study. Defect reports were reviewed and none were found applicable to rotating-frame hemolysis simulations. Requiredlevel 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy test or method of manufactured solutions (MMS) demonstrating expected convergence rate for governing equations.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was performed for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver in a simplified rotating-frame geometry. Observed spatial order of accuracy was 1.92, consistent with the nominal second-order scheme. Temporal discretization was verified separately using a manufactured transient solution. Both tests passed the acceptance threshold of p >= 1.8. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) reported for QoI; GCI < 5% on fine grid.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted at the design operating point (6 L/min, 3000 RPM). GCI on the fine mesh (8.4 M cells) was 3.1% for volume-averaged shear stress and 2.7% for hemolysis index, both below the 5% threshold. Intermediate and coarse meshes showed monotonic convergence. The fine mesh was used for all production runs. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented and traceable; boundary conditions in CFD model derived from measured values with stated uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All bench test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, inlet pressure, fluid temperature, hematocrit) were recorded with calibrated instrumentation traceable to NIST standards. Measurement uncertainties were propagated to CFD boundary conditions using a first-order Taylor series method. Inlet velocity profiles were derived from ultrasonic flow meter readings. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation metric) computed and within pre-specified acceptance band.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against published FDA experimental data at five operating points. Mean absolute percentage error was 8.4% across operating points, within the pre-specified 15% acceptance band. Bland-Altman analysis showed no systematic bias. The model successfully ranked operating points by hemolysis severity in agreement with experiment. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI used in validation directly maps to clinical decision metric; mapping documented.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which maps directly to the relative hemolysis index (RH) used in the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 versus predicate). The mapping between NIH and RH is documented in the V&V plan. Secondary QoI (wall shear stress distribution) is used diagnostically to identify high-risk zones. Required level 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are conducted on a geometry, fluid, and operating regime that is sufficiently similar to the COU geometry and conditions to support extrapolation of credibility conclusions; similarity is demonstrated quantitatively or through structured expert elicitation with documented consensus.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were performed using the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump benchmark geometry, which differs from the production CPB device in impeller blade count (5 vs. 6), volute exit angle (72° vs. 65°), and nominal operating speed range (2500–4500 RPM vs. 3000–5500 RPM). The team conducted a structured similarity assessment across eight geometric and operational parameters. Six of eight parameters were rated 'highly similar' by the three-member expert panel; the remaining two (blade count and speed range overlap) were rated 'moderately similar.' The panel concluded, based on 40+ combined years of turbomachinery CFD experience and reference to analogous pump validation studies in the literature (Morrison et al. 2019; Hariharan et al. 2018), that the physical mechanisms governing hemolysis — viscous shear in the blade passage and volute tongue — are sufficiently captured by the benchmark geometry to support credibility transfer to the production device. Sensitivity analyses showed that hemolysis index predictions varied by less than 12% across the range of blade-count and speed-range perturbations explored in a parametric CFD sweep. On this basis the assessment team judged the validation evidence adequate to support the COU. The required level for this factor at MRL 2 with High decision consequence is 3, reflecting the expectation of quantitative similarity metrics with uncertainty bounds; the achieved level is 2, reflecting that the similarity assessment relied on structured expert judgment and parametric sensitivity rather than a fully quantified extrapolation uncertainty analysis with confidence intervals. The team considers the expert consensus and sensitivity data sufficient to proceed, noting that the 12% sensitivity bound falls within the 15% model acceptance band established for output comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; vendor documentation sufficient.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, numerical solver error beyond code verification is not required. Vendor release notes and internal QA records are considered sufficient. Factor scoped to level 1 per MRL 2 guidance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; standard operator training records sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment beyond documented operator training is not required at MRL 2. All analysts held current ANSYS Fluent certification. Factor scoped to level 1 per MRL 2 guidance."
    },
    {
